{% import "product-components.njk" as pc %}

<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Reporting</strong> standardizes a <strong>unified report substrate</strong> &mdash; one
    normalized model that <em>every</em> producer targets and <em>every</em> renderer and adapter agrees
    on. Today each report rolls its own output: <code>check:standards</code>,
    <code>check:app-conformance</code>, <code>check:readiness</code>, the conformance burndown, and the
    capability-manifest report each diverge in shape, styling, and export, and a future run against a
    <em>real external app</em> would arrive in a foreign format entirely. Web Reporting fixes the shape so
    the same view serves many producers.
  </p>
  <p>
    It fixes one thing &mdash; the <strong>Report model</strong> &mdash; the normalized schema of
    <em>sources, sections, findings, severities, scores, and series</em>. Like the
    <a href="/projects/webdecisions/">Decision Record</a> it is a <strong>schema-only interchange
    contract: the model shape is the lock, and there is no provider on the model itself</strong>. What earns
    it a <strong>Protocol</strong> (not just an intent) is the multi-vendor format-interop story: SARIF,
    JUnit, coverage, and SonarQube all exchange the same <em>kind</em> of artifact, so ingest/export
    <strong>adapters</strong> &mdash; not bespoke viewers &mdash; bridge each foreign format bottom-up into
    the pivot. An intent would be UX-only and wrong for a data-interchange contract.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(79, 70, 229, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #4f46e5; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #4338ca; font-size: 1rem;">Not a catalog, not the engine, not the adapters</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      A <strong>catalog</strong> page (<a href="/protocols/">/protocols/</a>, <a href="/intents/">/intents/</a>)
      renders a <em>registry</em>; Web Reporting renders <strong>findings and results over time</strong>.
      It does not <em>produce</em> the findings &mdash; an underwriting decision, a conformance check, a CI
      run all do, and each emits the same model. And it is not the <a href="/projects/webadapters/">Web
      Adapters</a> bridge itself: the ingest/export adapters that translate SARIF/JUnit/coverage are the
      <em>swappable</em> half this protocol makes possible; this slice fixes only the schema they target.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

